{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The request sent to the external API always includes the complete list of valid taxonomy labels.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: failure is at a module boundary (request-builder -> API client payload handoff), not just isolated parsing logic. REAL-INFRA: no real OS/network/subprocess is required; an in-process fake transport can capture the outgoing payload. MOCK-HIDE: a fake that records actual serialized request will still catch omission/order/field-shape bugs. LLM-DEP: correctness does not depend on model judgment, only request contents. MULTI-STEP: no agent pipeline. Rejection-gate: System rejected because behavior text is about request contents, not real network conditions; Agentic rejected because no claim about model output quality/decision.","test_description":"Wire classifier module to a fake API client that records requests; invoke classify with a taxonomy and assert the dispatched payload contains the full taxonomy label list exactly where the provider contract expects it.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.35,"Integration":0.55,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.04,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When the API returns a label that is not in the taxonomy, the module returns \"unknown\" instead of forwarding the unexpected value to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: real failure typically appears in adapter->normalizer->public return path (handoff of provider label), not only in a single pure function. REAL-INFRA: no real network needed; stubbed provider response is sufficient. MOCK-HIDE: mocking at too high a level (bypassing adapter output) could hide bugs, so test should include module wiring. LLM-DEP: no dependence on model quality, only deterministic post-processing of returned string. MULTI-STEP: no multi-agent chain. Rejection-gate: Agentic rejected because behavior text targets invalid